comments: I would put this same comment for other surveys that ask about vaping.    I think it is incredibly unclear what constitutes as "vaping", for those who have tried it a few times but don't do it regularly. For example, I can explain my history with vaping, and explain how I was unsure how to answer certain questions.     I was in a relationship with someone for ~2 years who "vaped" on a daily basis, but it was only occasionally with nicotine (and always low doses of nicotine). Sometimes he would vape just for the flavours or to do tricks with the vapour, and would use juice that did not contain any nicotine. Does that still count as vaping? If so, I vaped everyday (couple puffs here and there) for probably a year, but this was usually (90% of the time) juice that did not contain nicotine. It wasn't an "e-cigarette" though, I don't think. It was shaped more like a box/"mod". Is that vaping?     In my current relationship, my partner and I have gone through periods where we "vape" more days than not (since the start of the pandemic), but I don't think it's the type of vaping that this survey is asking about. The vape we have (Pax 2) is a dry herb vaporizer for marijuana. There is no vape juice, no nicotine. You just put dry weed in it and it heats it up (I think).     I think it would be good to very clearly define what the survey means by vaping (or by e-cigarettes), include pictures of what you mean and pictures/descriptions of what you DON'T mean.     I also think it would be good in advertisement campaigns to describe the risks that are associated with different "types" of vaping. For example, I have NO idea if using the dry herb vaporizer for marijuana is harmful to my health (and if it is, how much more or less harmful it is than smoking a joint, or consuming edibles, or vaping nicotine, etc.). The messaging on vaping is incredibly confusing and I often find myself thinking "well, all of the ads talk about how bad vaping NICOTINE is, but I'm not vaping nicotine, so this doesn't apply to me". I wish I knew the risks of what I'm doing and I wish the messaging were more clear.

nrttryexp_1: I've smoked 3 cigarettes in the last 20 months, all at once in a period of intense stress. I smoked 4 or 5 in the 2 previous years, again all at once in a period of intense stress. I don't ever get nicotine cravings--even when I do smoke, I don't have an actual desire to, it's a calculated move because I know that the cigarette will relax my body. Because of this, I don't think that NRT would be useful to me personally. I do think it's wonderful that the Expand Project provides this, though!     Also, I gave a negative response to the Expand video because I found it unbearably corny. I suspect it's aimed at people younger than me (I'm 30) but even when I was a teenager, I would have found it cheesy and felt condescended to. That said, I think it sound like a great project--the marketing just wasn't the right tone for me.
comments: I had a lot of trouble answering the questions about quitting, and I often wasn't sure what the most accurate response would be. This is because my smoking is so erratic. I've smoked 3 cigarettes in the last 20 months, all at once in a period of intense stress. I smoked 4 or 5 in the 2 previous years, again all at once in a period of intense stress. I might never smoke again and I feel no temptation to smoke--certainly I hope I don't. So I'm not sure exactly how to approach the concept of quitting. I smoke when I'm having an anxiety attack, have no other coping strategy available, and am obliged to to interact socially with people and pretend to be fine. In this situation I smoke not because I have any craving for a cigarette, but because I know that I will have a chemical reaction to the cigarette that will physically relax my body. Under normal circumstances, when I don't have to enter a social situation, my reaction to stress or to an anxiety attack is never to smoke. I have other coping mechanisms that are healthier and work better.     Because of this, I really wasn't sure how to respond to questions about whether I had quit, whether I had tried to quit, and seeking support. I just wanted to note this, because I'm sure my responses to that section seemed somewhat self-contradictory at times.

I am currently in an investigation with the City but may file a late Human Rights or Occupational Safty complaint. If emotionally capable I might go to one of the two journalist's who are intrested in my story as a last resort. Regardless, all this has accumulated mentally and I smoked weed for the first time (Nov 2021) because of these incidents happening on the bases of race and sexuality. I have smoked twice now and I may continue to do so very lightly (less than once a month) and/or use CBD oil. I may stop when this ordeal is over and I can heal from this situation. I state this b/c I firmly believe that if you are a minority or apart if the LGBTQ+ community you deal with more stressor as a result. Thus you may be more prone to smoke or use other substances.

risk_thoughts_1: I think decades of research linking cigarette consumption to increased risk of cancer is very well established in the scientific community. I think there is a strong general consensus that cigarette smoking causes cancer. Smoking cigarettes daily is an extremely high risk health-behaviour regardless of the psychological or social-emotional reasons why people do it (e.g.: stress, boredom, fun, socializing, appetite suppressant, fitting in, etc). The medical scientific and academic research on e-cigarettes is still in development and not as generally agreed upon. However, it wouldn't surprise me if smoking e-cigarettes was also strongly linked to developing respiratory problems, lung damage, throat or mouth cancers, lung cancers, neurocognitive issues, etc.
rates_thoughts_1: Similar to some research on LGBTQ+ alcohol consumption, it wouldn't surprise me if LGBTQ+ folks disproportionately engaged in smoking behaviours at higher rates in comparison to heterosexual, cisgender youth and young adults.
reasons_thts_1: To be clear, not every LGBT+ person feels comfortable being referred to by the historical q-slur. Nevertheless, even in a seemingly progressive country such as Canada, many LGBT youth and adults experience the pressure to be heteronormative or hetero-passing/cis-passing in their families and cultural or religious communities. Despite having marriage equality and pro-LGBT+ Canadian laws, there remains many neighborhoods and streets in parts of Canada where being perceived as LGBT increases one's risk for bullying, assault, verbal abuse, hate speech, hate crime, and/or street harassment. I have lived in Canada my entire life but remain 'closeted' even as an adult in my late 20s due to heteronormative and homophobic/biphobia family religious norms and cultural attitudes in my community. I am only 'out' to 1 person. Some people may not fully understand why in so-called 'progressive Canada' there are still 'closeted', 'hidden', or 'secret' LGBT people hiding their sexual and gender orientation from their families, communities, and peers. Having to live a repressed closeted lie, where I am basically celibate, abstinent, single and not dating because being 'out' causes too much emotional abuse, verbal abuse, family arguments and family strain, increases my feelings of depression and makes me feel like life is passing me by and I am missing out on opportunities for LGBT people my age. Being 'closeted' due to cultural and religious homophobia/biphobia has a negative impact on my mental health and well-being. I firmly believe that overall, LGBT people in Canada still struggle with stigma, heteronormative pressure, religious and cultural oppression within various communities and Canadian (political or ideological) spaces, that negatively impacts our social determinants of health and survival.
where_support_1: Google? I would have to research for specific resources. I think the mainstream public interest in addressing smoking has drastically decreased over the years and has been replaced by other public health campaigns. I remember as a pre-teen and teenager seeing TV ads discouraging smoking and promoting resources but these ads are no longer airing, and other anti-smoking campaigns that still air do not air frequently or generate much buzz/viral attention. Most people seem to have largely moved on from smoking as a hot-button cultural and political issue and the research on smoking being carcinogenic is assumed and taken for granted. If you're still smoking tobacco and nicotine cigarettes in the 2020s, the assumption is that you already know the health risks associated and that you simply do not care and it is a willfully ignorant decision a person is making for themselves. If they really wanted help, they would get it. There's nicotine patches and gum, and urge-suppressing mouth sprays.

comments: I felt like the questions about how acceptable smoking was was confusing because I didn't know what it was measuring. To clarify my feelings, I feel like I understand that smoking has a number of significant health risks, and in an ideal world people would have healthier ways of coping with stress. I do have a family member who died of lung cancer and as a result I would never smoke myself. However, I don't feel like I am in a position to judge how people cope with their stress given how pervasive it is in my community. Helping people out and being helped out so people are able to care for themselves and not die of suicide or suffer medical neglect is a pretty common thing in my life. I don't see smoking as good via the health risks, but I would never judge someone on a personal level for smoking. Also, a lot of people in my life are on psychiatric medication with known serious side effects and risks that are in some cases worse than cigarettes. rates_thoughts_1: Excuse my vulgarity but honestly my first thought was "yeah, no shit." Substance abuse of any kind is higher among all groups of minorities and it compounds when the groups an individual belongs to overlap. Queer and trans young adults also have higher suicide rates, higher crime rates, lower income, etc. But that's not to say inherently because you're queer/trans you'll absolutely fall prey to things like drugs - I haven't. What I think is that we've cultivated a society that profits off of those stuck in difficult situations and addictions are great for the economy. Barriers have been created intentionally to exploit anyone that can't fit into the mold of "Straight, white, neurotypical, rich, cis-male" and even though many of those barriers have been abolished in policies/law, they are the roots for problems we face today.    Have you ever woken up and known that the world wasn't on your side? That everyone you met in a day wasn't capable, wouldn't even try, to see a situation from your perspective? What about that doesn't make you want to reach for a smoke and try to feel something other than numb for a couple minutes? And as a business, do you see how creating misery could be profitable?
comments: It would be nice if there were options for "tried/experimented." I've only vaped once and the options didn't seem to reflect that.    Also I think it's important to bring up that even if smoking has become a big part of queer culture, there are still reasons queer people start smoking outside of that and those issues need to be addressed to see any real change. Smoking didn't 'become a part of queer culture' out of nowhere and it's important not to conflate the symptom for the disease.
